post_text:
We are happy to announce that VESD Nutrition Services will be resuming community meal services on Tuesday, September 8, 2020. This means that ALL CHILDREN between the ages of 3-18, not just VESD students, are eligible to receive five days worth of meals every week. The community feeding service is part of a program through the USDA that will last until the end of this calendar year.

VESD families will still need to present their student ID’s and pick up meals at their own school site unless arrangements are made in advance with our Nutrition Services department at 760-245-5221.

All non-VESD children will be issued a card with their food bags that must be presented at each meal pick-up.

Meal service is limited to one bag per seven-day period. Please follow all appropriate precautions against COVID-19 when on VESD campuses, including wearing face coverings, practicing social distancing, and remaining inside your vehicle.

Community meal service hours are Fri & Tue from 11AM-1PM at all 18 VESD schools.

Last Monday, we sent out a survey to all VESD families via email. Since then, over 2,000 parents have given their feedback on reopening school in August - Thank you! Your feedback is crucial as we plan for the upcoming school year.

We want to make it very clear that our first choice would be to have all of our students on our campuses full-time, just like it was pre-COVID. However, we need to prepare if it's not possible to do so safely and according to the guidelines presented by the CDC and Ca Department of Public Health.

If you haven't completed the survey, please do so as soon as possible. Check your email inboxes, or spam folders, for instructions. If you haven't received the survey email, please give us your contact info by clicking the link below. You'll receive your invite within 24 hours.

Thank you all for your input and teamwork! #VESDstrongertogether

https://forms.gle/6KZnaHSc8GwwEsXFA

post_text:
Due to Coronavirus (COVID-19), children who are eligible for free or reduced-price meals at school will get extra food benefits. These food benefits are called Pandemic EBT or P-EBT benefits. P-EBT benefits help families in California buy food when schools are closed because of the coronavirus emergency.

Families will get up to $365 per eligible child on their P-EBT card to use on food and groceries.

Families with children who get CalFresh, Medi-Cal or Foster Care benefits do not need to apply. Most received their P-EBT card in the mail during the month of May.

Families with children who are eligible for free or reduced-price meals and who do not get their P-EBT card in the mail by the end of May must apply online before July 15, 2020. The online application is available at ca.p-ebt.org.

Please note this is NOT a VESD program. If you have any questions, visit https://www.cdss.ca.gov/home/pandemic-ebt.

post_text:
We're officially on summer break. :)

Our deepest gratitude to all of you - staff, students, parents, and the community-at-large. The COVID pandemic has created challenges unlike anything we've ever had to deal with, but with your support, adaptability, and perseverance, we made it this far.

There's still a long way to go, and we're working as hard as we can to prepare for next year. We know that there will be new obstacles and challenges because that's what 2020 is all about. But no matter what happens, we'll be ready to provide our students with safe, supporting, and engaging learning experiences because that is the VESD way.

We wish you all a safe, relaxing, and refreshing summer!

post_text:
Important public service announcement from the California Department of Social Services:

Pandemic EBT (P-EBT) benefits will be available for eligible California families soon!

Due to Coronavirus (COVID-19), children who are eligible for free or reduced-price meals at school will get extra food benefits. These food benefits are called Pandemic EBT or P-EBT benefits. P-EBT benefits help families in California buy food when schools are closed because of the coronavirus emergency.

Families will get up to $365 per eligible child on their P-EBT card to use on food and groceries.

Families with children who get CalFresh, Medi-Cal or Foster Care benefits do not need to apply. Most will get their P-EBT card in the mail during the month of May. P-EBT cards will begin arriving in May, 2020.

Families with children who are eligible for free or reduced-price meals and who do not get their P-EBT card in the mail, must apply online before June 30, 2020. The online application will launch in late May.

Please visit the Pandemic EBT website for additional information.

post_text:
Good Afternoon VESD families. By now, you've most likely heard the recommendations from the governor and the state superintendent of schools regarding school closures. So, we must formally announce that all VESD schools will remain closed through the remainder of the 2019/2020 school year.

Although we are disappointed to make this announcement, we can now focus 100% on delivering high-quality distance education to our students while also preventing the spread of COVID-19 in our community.

While we won't be able to see each other face to face, we look forward to connecting online, over the phone, and through the car windows of our drive through meal programs.

We encourage you all to continue practicing social distancing guidelines. If we all work together, we can flatten the curve. Thank you for your understanding and patience.

post_text:
The VESD Junior Olympics are kicking off tomorrow, May 8, with students from Brentwood, Challenger, Endeavour, Galileo, Lomitas, Mojave Vista, Puesta del Sol, and Village competing.

On May 9, Del Rey, Discovery, Green Tree East, Irwin, Liberty, Mountain View Montessori, Park View, and West Palms take the field.

We wanted to share some quick tips to make sure that the students who are participating in this week's Junior Olympics are safe, healthy, and perform to the best of their ability.

First, sleep is important so please make sure they get plenty of rest.

Second – nutrition is key - eat a healthy and hearty breakfast.

Third – it’s going to be warm, so drink plenty of water to avoid dehydration. Bring sunscreen and more water to beat the heat.

The event starts at 9am on both days at Silverado High School in Victorville and you are all invited to cheer on the kids.

But don’t worry if you can’t make it, you can catch all the action live on our youtube page at www.youtube.com/thevesdway.

Thanks! We hope to see you all there!

Please RSVP in the at the event below. See you then!

post_text:
Dear Parents/Guardians,

On December 17, 2018, Dominique Butler, a proctor at Lomitas Elementary, was arrested on suspicion of sexual assault against a family member. The district placed Mr. Butler on leave immediately after learning about the allegations and is working diligently to assist with the sheriff’s investigation.

Although law enforcement believes this to be an isolated incident, the district and the investigators are requesting the public’s help to determine if there were any other victims. If you have any additional information, please contact the district office at 760-245-1691 or Deputy Clancy or Sergeant Alexander with the Apple Valley Police Department at 760-240-7000, case # 181806096.

Victor Elementary School District remains determined to providing the safest possible environment for our students.

post_text:
Media Advisory from the City of Victorville

Road Closures Due to Storm-Related Flooding

WHEN: Today, Dec. 6, until further notice

DESCRIPTION: Due to storm-related flooding, portions of Pebble Beach Drive, Hughes Road and Avalon Drive are now closed.

Signage is in place. Motorists are advised to utilize alternate routes and to exercise extreme caution. Out of an abundance of caution, drivers should never drive through standing water.

Traffic in the area of these road closures could be impacted and delays can be expected. Motorists should budget additional time for their commutes as appropriate.

Questions can be directed to (760) 241-6365.

WHERE:
Pebble Beach Drive – between Arrowhead Drive and Victoria Road

Pebble Beach Drive – between Arrowhead Drive and Hughes Road

Hughes Road – between Arrowhead Drive and Avalon Drive

Avalon Drive – between Hughes Road and Molino Drive

# # #

post_text: Important Message for Mojave Vista Families - On Monday, October 15, the City of Victorville will begin a new construction phase on 7th Avenue as part of the Safe Routes to School Project. The work will include additional sidewalks and improved crosswalks with flashing lights. Although the construction team will work around the bell schedule, please allow additional time for pickup/dropoff as delays are expected. Additional crossing guards will be on hand to ensure walkers are able to cross 7th Avenue safely during construction. The project is expected to last 4 to 6 weeks.

UPDATE 9:53AM - The Sheriff's Department has given the all-clear. Safeguard Status at Puesta del Sol and Challenger has been lifted. Campus will return to normal status. Thank you.

UPDATE 9:27AM - Puesta del Sol has been downgraded to Safeguard Status. Safeguard Status means that the campus will remain on heightened security, however, students will be allowed to move around campus with an escort, instruction will proceed as normal. At this time, Challenger Elementary is also on Safeguard Status

Puesta del Sol Elementary is currently on lockdown due to law enforcement activity near the school. Although the incident is not directly related to our site, we have taken these steps to secure the campus out of an abundance of caution. Thank you for your understanding. We will continue to post updates as they become available.

Attention VESD families, the Victorville Christmas Parade hosted by the Victorville Kiwanis Club is taking place this Saturday, Dec. 2 at 10 a.m. The parade will take place on a two-mile stretch of 7th Street in Old Town Victorville between La Paz Drive and Mojave Drive. This year’s event will feature 90 entries including marching bands, military groups, car clubs, civic organizations, Santa Claus and best of all, VESD kiddos performing with their schools!

The parade is free and open to the public! For more info on the Victorville Christmas Parade, please contact (760) 843-6190.

From the City of Victorville:

Media Alert
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE
November 27, 2017

Road Closure

WHAT: Road Closures Due to Traffic Collision and Downed Power Pole

WHEN: Monday, November 27th, 2017 until further notice

WHERE: Mojave Drive at I-15 Southbound off-ramp
Mojave Drive at Condor Road
Village Drive at Culebra Road

DESCRIPTION: Due to a traffic collision and downed power pole, there is a hard closure on Mojave Drive between Condor Road and the I-15 freeway south bound off-ramp, and Village Drive at Culebra Road in Victorville, Calif. Pedestrians and vehicles will not be allowed to travel through the affected area.

Detours will be posted. Motorists are encouraged to exercise caution, obey all traffic devices and signage and to utilize alternate routes.

Questions can be directed to (760) 241-6365.
